      <h1>The Ultimate Guide to Cinnamon</h1>
      <p>Ceylon vs Cassia, sweet vs savory, and everything you need to know about buying and using the world's favorite baking spice.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>The Two Faces of Cinnamon</h2>
      <p>Cinnamon is the inner bark of various tree species from the genus Cinnamomum. It is one of the oldest known spices, highly prized in antiquity and literally the stuff of legends (ancient spice traders fabricated elaborate tales involving giant birds to protect their sources). Today, it is a ubiquitous pantry staple.</p>
      <p>However, what most consumers in North America and Europe think of as "cinnamon" is actually a completely different species from the "true" cinnamon used in other parts of the world. Understanding the profound differences between these two main varieties—Cassia and Ceylon—is the key to unlocking the full potential of this incredible spice.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Cassia Cinnamon: The Bold Classic</h2>
      <p>If you buy a generic bottle of ground cinnamon at a North American supermarket, you are buying Cassia cinnamon (Cinnamomum cassia or related species like C. burmannii). Originating from China and Southeast Asia (particularly Indonesia and Vietnam), Cassia is the dominant cinnamon in global commerce due to its robust flavor and lower cost.</p>
      <p><strong>Physical Characteristics:</strong> Cassia bark is thick, hard, and forms a single, rigid curl (quill). It is very difficult to grind at home without a specialized heavy-duty spice grinder; attempting to grind Cassia bark in a standard coffee grinder may break the blades.</p>
      <p><strong>Flavor Profile:</strong> Cassia is pungent, spicy, bold, and intensely sweet. This is the classic "cinnamon roll" flavor. It holds up exceptionally well to high heat and heavy sugar, making it the undisputed champion of American and European baking.</p>
      <p><strong>The Coumarin Factor:</strong> Cassia contains significant levels of a naturally occurring compound called coumarin. In very large doses, coumarin can cause liver damage. While normal culinary use is entirely safe, individuals taking high-dose cinnamon supplements for blood sugar management are generally advised to seek out Ceylon cinnamon instead.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Ceylon Cinnamon: The "True" Cinnamon</h2>
      <p>Ceylon cinnamon (Cinnamomum verum) is native to Sri Lanka (formerly Ceylon) and southern parts of India. Historically, it was considered the only "true" cinnamon.</p>
      <p><strong>Physical Characteristics:</strong> Ceylon bark is paper-thin, delicate, and forms multiple, tightly wound layers resembling a cigar. It is brittle and crumbles easily, making it very simple to grind fresh at home in a standard mortar and pestle or spice grinder.</p>
      <p><strong>Flavor Profile:</strong> Ceylon is vastly different from Cassia. It is much more subtle, floral, citrusy, and complex, with a lighter, less aggressively spicy-sweet profile. If you substitute Ceylon for Cassia in a heavy baked good (like a carrot cake), the flavor will easily get lost.</p>
      <p><strong>Best Uses:</strong> Ceylon shines in delicate applications where its nuanced, floral notes can be appreciated. It is perfect for steeping in teas, dusting over fresh fruit, flavoring light custards or panna cotta, and is heavily featured in authentic Mexican (where it is known as canela) and South Asian savory cooking.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Sweet vs. Savory Applications</h2>
      <p>In the West, cinnamon is almost exclusively associated with sweet baking: pies, cookies, cakes, and breakfast pastries. However, globally, cinnamon is just as likely to show up in a savory dish.</p>
      <p><strong>Savory Culinary Uses:</strong> Cinnamon provides a foundational background warmth and subtle sweetness to savory dishes without turning them into desserts. It is a critical component of:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Middle Eastern & North African Cuisine:</strong> Used in tagines, spiced rice (pilaf), and meat rubs (like ras el hanout or baharat). It pairs exceptionally well with lamb and beef, cutting through their richness.</li>
        <li><strong>Indian Cuisine:</strong> Whole cinnamon sticks (often Cassia for its durability) are tempered in hot oil along with cardamom and cloves at the beginning of cooking curries and biryanis.</li>
        <li><strong>Greek Cuisine:</strong> A touch of cinnamon is the secret ingredient in authentic Greek Moussaka and Pastitsio meat sauces.</li>
        <li><strong>Mexican Cuisine:</strong> Ceylon cinnamon (canela) is essential for authentic mole sauces and traditional carnitas preparations.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Pro Tip for Savory Cooking:</strong> When using cinnamon in savory dishes (like a chili or a braise), use it sparingly. The goal is to make the diner wonder, "What is that warming background note?" rather than explicitly tasting "cinnamon."</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Buying and Storing Guide</h2>
      <p>Because pre-ground cinnamon loses its volatile oils (primarily cinnamaldehyde) rapidly, it is highly recommended to buy it whole and grind it as needed.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>For Baking:</strong> Buy high-quality Vietnamese (Saigon) Cassia. It has the highest essential oil content (often up to 6%) and provides the strongest, sweetest flavor. You can buy it pre-ground since grinding Cassia at home is difficult, but buy it in small quantities from reputable spice merchants rather than generic supermarket brands.</li>
        <li><strong>For Savory/Delicate Uses:</strong> Buy whole Ceylon (Sri Lankan) cinnamon quills. They are easy to grind fresh and provide unparalleled floral complexity.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Store all cinnamon in airtight containers in a cool, dark cupboard. Ground cinnamon should be replaced every 6 to 12 months, while whole sticks can last for several years.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>What is the difference between Ceylon and Cassia cinnamon?</h3>
      <p>Ceylon (true cinnamon) is delicate, crumbly, floral, and less sweet. Cassia is the thick, hard bark most common in the US; it is pungent, spicy, and intensely sweet. Cassia also contains much higher levels of coumarin.</p>
      <h3>Which cinnamon is better for baking?</h3>
      <p>For classic American baked goods like cinnamon rolls or pumpkin pie, Cassia is generally preferred for its strong, robust, classic "cinnamon" flavor that stands up well to heat and sugar. Ceylon is better for delicate pastries or teas.</p>
      <h3>Is too much cinnamon toxic?</h3>
      <p>Cassia cinnamon contains coumarin, which can be toxic to the liver in very high doses. However, normal culinary use (a teaspoon or two a day) is perfectly safe. Ceylon cinnamon contains trace, negligible amounts of coumarin.</p>
    </div>

